					   <td>

			
			
			



<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Brad follows up on downtime and the Manastone</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=325415" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><A href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/044791.html">All about Downtime</a></B><P>

I'm bumping a couple of older threads in a sense, because I'd like more discussion and brainstorming on downtime in MMORPGs in general and EQ specifically. The following are three posts I made that might have been missed because the threads became pretty large. <P>

The first deals with why downtime is used as a penalty for death and inefficient grouping, the second deals with travel, and the third talks about why downtime has nothing to do with us 'making more money.'.<P>

Anyway, let's see if we jumpstart this discussion again... I'd love to see this debated here and elsewhere.<P>

---------<P>

<I>The fundamental advancement mechanism in MMORPGs is Time Invested; therefore, Time Lost needs to be the fundamental death penalty if the principle of risk vs. reward is to be preserved.<P>

The time lost can be in the form of experience loss, an experience debt (a cool idea, btw), items lost (providing it takes time to acquire items), corpse retrievals, etc. <P>

As a corollary, being efficient in terms of time spent is the quickest way to advance (assuming advancing quickly is your goal, of course). Downtime, which is likewise often debated and criticized, is also a penalty based on the Time Invested/Time Lost principle. Minimizing or even eliminating downtime using intelligent tactics in a well-balanced group is an efficient time investment. Failing to do so incurs a Time Lost penalty, though probably not as severe as dying.<P>

-Brad</I><P>

------<P>

<I>Seriously, as I posted recently, downtime is most often used as a penalty (for death, inefficient grouping, etc.). A challenge within the game, therefore, is to be efficient and to minimize downtime.<P>

This isn't as applicable to travel (well, unless you consider teleportation spells), but please realize that there is a balance we've tried to achieve between tedium and losing how big a world feels and the sense of accomplishment from travel.<P>

This probably opens up a new area of discussion and debate, that being how does one create a virtual world in an MMOG that is large, where exploration is important, where players feel accomplished after traveling great distances, yet isn't tedious when it comes to frequent traveling....<P>

In a recent discussion an example came up: Frodo traveling to Mount Doom was exciting and perilous the first time, but if he had to go there over and over again, it would get tedious. So, is it possible to set up a system such that the fun and accomplishment of traveling to that far away, exotic land is maintained, yet repeated travel isn't tedious?<P>

I think we got closer to this goal with the way the dragon teleportation works in Velious...<P>

Anyway, just some food for thought.<P>

-Brad</I><P>

-------<P>

<I>Would you guys stop with the 'downtime is there to keep people playing to make VI more $'... sheesh <P>

The way we keep people playing is by making a fun and challenging game that people feel compelled to play... by focusing on character development, an immersive and interesting world, and by creating an environment where people can easily develop online relationships.<P>

Downtime is there as a penalty (please read my other posts). It's not supposed to be fun, and the challenge is to avoid it. <P>

If people thought there was too much downtime and that the majority of their experience playing wasn't any fun, they'd leave. It wouldn't KEEP people playing and make us money, rather it would have the OPPOSITE effect.<P>

Some of you might find this hard to believe, but the EQ teams are a bunch of gamers who want to make a great game. We NEVER talk about money and profits and revenue at tuning meetings. We talk about what would make the game better, or what needs to be addressed to fix balance issues, etc.<P>

In addition, there are no corporate suits breathing down our necks, pushing profits and such. That didn't happen when we were part of 989, nor did it happen as Verant, and it's not happening at SOE.<P>

Why? Well, most good game companies know to leave their creative people alone as long as they're making great and profitable games. And guess what? EQ continues to be a huge success.<P>

As a final note, just to really illuminate how ludicrous the 'downtime = more bucks for VI' argument is, let's talk a bit about bandwidth. It's really, really expensive. Were we purely out to make the maximum dollars possible, we'd scheme and plan to make a game where you hardly logged on at all, but still paid us ten bucks a month. That's right: the most profit comes from a subscriber who plays only occasionally. The guys who play crazy hours every day cost us more due to bandwidth used.<P>

That's right, casual gamers, we make the most money off of you! *evil cackle* :)<P>

-Brad</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/044708.html">Brad? Can I have my Manastone back now?</a></B><P>

Since the main reason you gave us for "nerfing" the manastone, ie. "No one will let me on a Planes Raid unless I have one", is pretty much moot at this point, can you un-nerf the manastone to work everywhere again? With the new armor and other item abilities, I can't see a reason why the manastone shouldn't work again in the Planes and new zones. Please?<P>

<B>Elfvyra: no.<P>

sorry :(<P>

-Brad</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
